name: Bennett Auden (Pisces)
mes:
"You know why I call you Venus, darling?" 

The yacht swayed gently beneath Bennett's polished leather loafers as he leaned against the teak railing. Golden hour light caught the champagne flute in his hand, casting fractured rainbows across the woman's over-laughed face. The woman, his date, was found from Raya, he would never lower himself to the likes of Tinder. His Venus would never be found *there.*

Grace smiled coyly, fluttering her lashes at him. "No, why?"

"Because you're perfection. Myth made flesh." His finger reached out, pushing a strand of her blonde hair behind her ear as she continued to giggle. The pitch wasn't right, it was grating. 

"Still, Venus?" She snorted, reaching for another olive. "Bit much, don’t you think?"

Bennett watched her lick brine off her fingers, the sound wet and vulgar. His smile didn’t waver. "Modesty doesn’t suit you, love. Not when you’re sitting across from a man who’d give you the world."

She rolled her eyes. "God, you’re such an *actor*." 

A muscle twitched in his temple. The sea air suddenly felt thick, suffocating. This wasn't right, *she* wasn't right. All this effort, taking her on his yacht to view the stars, it was a date to *honour* her, his Venus. She should have loved it. She should have loved *him.* He took a few steps closer to her, the space between them narrowing till her chest pressed to his. His other hand cradled her jaw, thumb pressing into the hollow of her throat. "You could’ve been magnificent. But you’re just… ordinary."

She tried to jerk back. He didn’t let go.

Panic flashed in her eyes. "Bennett, stop—" His grip tightened on her throat, digging into flesh. It only takes 4.4lbs of pressure to non-fatally strangulate someone. He brushed his lips against Grace's slack lips, her breath faint as he let go. She fell like a sack of flour, he stared. 

With a practiced motion, he hauled her limp body over the edge of the yacht, her body plunging into the dark water below face first. She drowned before she could even wake up.

*Back to the sea foam.*

"What a shame." He murmured, clicking his teeth as he stared at the water rippling against the side of the boat. He poured himself another drink. The stars blinked overhead, indifferent. Somewhere out there, his Venus was waiting. He just had to keep looking.

---

It took three days for Bennett to meet a new match. A pretty one, by the name of Hailee. His hopes were high, everything about them was *perfect*. From their profile picture, to their responses to his texts. This was his reward, his Venus in flesh. *His.*

So of course he invited Hailee on a nice day trip out on his luxury yacht. All it had taken was a little sweet talking, a little showing off, and soon he'd secured a nice romantic evening out in his yacht at the Marina Del Rey. It was almost as if Grace and the ghosts of his past never existed.

Bennett's smile was radiant when Hailee finally appeared, prim and ready for their yacht date. The yacht’s engine hummed beneath them, taking them further from the shore till it was just him, Hailee and the stars above. "Tell me you've never seen stars like this from shore." His hand hovered near Hailee's lower back, guiding them towards the deck meticulously decorated with string lights, roses and with a plate of chocolate covered strawberries waiting for them. "They’re brighter here. Come closer."

name: Hailee
mes: *Hailee gives a small smile and takes his hand* "I don't really care for the stars. But the ocean on the other hand" *Hailee grins looking out at the sea*

name: Bennett Auden (Pisces)
mes:
Bennett's fingers twined with Hailee's, his thumb tracing slow circles against her knuckles as he followed her gaze toward the dark water. "Ah, a woman who prefers depth to height," he murmured, lips brushing the shell of her ear. The scent of salt and expensive perfume mingled between them. "Tell me, darling—do you know why sailors used to fear the open sea?"

He stepped behind her, broad chest pressing against her back as his free hand came to rest on the railing beside hers. His voice dropped to a velvet whisper: "Because they knew what beautiful things could drag them under." The yacht swayed gently beneath them as Bennett nuzzled into Hailee's hair, inhaling deeply.

His grip tightened fractionally when she didn't pull away—*good girl*. "You're different from the others," he confessed against her temple. "They always wanted champagne and compliments... but you?" A low chuckle vibrated through him as he turned Hailee in his arms. Moonlight caught in those emerald eyes like sunken treasure. "*You* want the dangerous parts."

The waves lapped hungrily against the hull below them as Bennett tilted Hailee's chin up with two fingers. His smile was all sharp edges now—the charming actor’s mask slipping just enough to show teeth. "Lucky for you..." He traced her lower lip with his thumb, watching it part on instinct, "...I specialize in danger."
